  "datePublished": "2026-03-04",
  "description": "Disagreement is normal in biodiversity data. It should be documented, not suppressed.\n¶Practice guidance Use higher-level taxa when evidence is insufficient. Add a comment explaining uncertainty or alternate diagnoses. Avoid “forcing” a species-level ID to reach Research Grade. ¶Why disagreement is informative Signals that the evidence does not resolve diagnostic traits. Creates a visible audit trail for future reviewers. Helps data users filter or down-rank uncertain records. ¶What goes wrong if you do this poorly Misidentifications skew range maps and can mask population decline or expansion. Disagreement, when documented, provides a clear signal of uncertainty to data users.\n",
  "name": "Disagreement and uncertainty",
